DATABASE

1, tb_students      | id: int(11), class_id: int(11), name: varchar(255), del_flag: tinyint(2), created_at: datetime, updated_at: datetime
2, tb_teachers      | id: int(11), name: varchar(255), del_flag: tinyint(2), created_at: datetime, updated_at: datetime
3, tb_classes       | id: int(11), name: varchar(255), del_flag: tinyint(2), created_at: datetime, updated_at: datetime
4, tb_subjects      | id: int(11), name: varchar(255), del_flag: tinyint(2), created_at: datetime, updated_at: datetime

5, tb_class_subject | id: int(11), class_id: int(11), subject_id: int(11), del_flag: tinyint(2), created_at: datetime, updated_at: datetime
6, tb_registers     | id: int(11), student_id: int(11), subject_id: int(11), del_flag: tinyint(2), created_at: datetime, updated_at: datetime
7, tb_teachings     | id: int(11), teacher_id: int(11), class_id: int(11), del_flag: tinyint(2), created_at: datetime, updated_at: datetime
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

I. List all students have registered both subjects X, Y

SELECT 
	tb_students.id, tb_students.name
FROM 
	tb_registers INNER JOIN tb_students ON tb_registers.student_id=tb_students.id AND tb_registers.del_flag=0
	             INNER JOIN tb_subject ON tb_registers.subject_id=tb_subject.id
WHERE 
	tb_subject.name='X' OR tb_subject.name='Y'
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

II, List the teachers teach more than five class

SELECT 
	tb_teachers.id, tb_teacher.name, COUNT(tb_teachings.class_id) AS ClassNumber
FROM 
	tb_teachings INNER JOIN tb_teachers ON tb_teachings.teacher_id=tb_teacher.id
WHERE
	ClassNumber>=5
GROUP BY
	tb_teachings.class_id
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

III, List the teachers teach a class that have at least 30 student return up

SELECT
	tb_teachers.id, tb_teacher.name, COUNT(tb_students.id) AS StudentNumber
FROM
	tb_class_subject INNER JOIN tb_teachings ON tb_class_subject.subject_id=tb_teachings.subject_id
			 RIGHT JOIN tb_teachers ON tb_teachings.teacher_id=tb_teachers.id
			 INNER JOIN tb_students ON tb_class_subject.class_id=tb_students.class_id
WHERE
	StudentNumber>=30
GROUP BY
	tb_students.id
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

IV. List all subjects of teacher G that have registered by student A

SELECT
	tb_subjects.id, tb_subjects.name, tb_teachers.name, tb_students.name
FROM
	tb_teachings INNER JOIN tb_class_subjects ON tb_teachings.class_id=tb_class_subjects.class_id
		     RIGHT JOIN tb_subjects ON tb_class_subjects.subject_id=tb_subjects.id
		     INNER JOIN tb_registers ON tb_subject.id=tb_registers.subject_id
		     RIGHT JOIN tb_teachers ON tb_teachings.teacher_id=tb_teacher.id
		     RIGHT JOIN tb_students ON tb_registers.student_id=tb_students.id
WHERE
	tb_teachers.name='G' AND tb_students.name='A'

Suppose that we have the 4 tables: readers, authors, books, borrows.. and
also relationships between 4 tables like:
1 Books -> Many Borrows.
1 Author -> Many Books
1 Reader -> Many Books
1 Reader -> Many Borrows.
We Can retrieve the data by SQL Like the syntax command below:

A. List the books have been borrowed more than 10 times in 2011
SELECT * FROM BOOKS
JOIN BORROWS ON BOOKS.ID= BORROWS.BOOK_ID
WHERE BORROWS.TIMES > 10 AND YEAR(BORROWS.DATE)= 2011;

B. List the readers has borrowed at least 10 different books:
SELECT * FROM READERS 
JOIN BORROWS ON READER.ID = BORROWS.READER_ID
HAVING COUNT(BORROWS.BOOK_ID)> 10;

C. List the books are being borrowed by a read in the preceding sentence (b)
SELECT * FROM BOOKS 
JOIN READERS ON BOOKS.ID = READERS.BOOKS_ID
WHERE READERS.ID IN (SELECT * FROM READERS 
JOIN BORROWS ON READER.ID = BORROWS.READER_ID
HAVING COUNT(BORROWS.BOOK_ID)> 10);

D. List of Stephen king books present no one is borrowing..
SELECT * FROM BOOKS 
JOIN AUTHORS ON AUTHORS.ID = BOOKS.AUTHOR_ID
WHERE NOT EXISTS (SELECT * FROM READER reader WHERE BOOKS.READER_ID =reader.ID);

CREATE TABLE musicians (
    musician_id INT NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,
    song_name varchar(255) NOT NULL,
    musician_name varchar(255) NOT NULL,
    PRIMARY KEY ( musician_id ), 
    FOREIGN KEY (song_name) REFERENCES songs(song_name) 
) ENGINE=INNODB;

CREATE TABLE songs (
    song_id INT NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,
    song_name varchar(255) NOT NULL,
    musician_name varchar(255) NOT NULL,
    PRIMARY KEY ( song_id ), 
    FOREIGN KEY (musician_name) REFERENCES musicians(musician_name) 
) ENGINE=INNODB;

CREATE TABLE singers (
    singer_id INT NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,
    song_name varchar(255) NOT NULL,
    singer_name varchar(255) NOT NULL,
    singer_age INT,
    PRIMARY KEY ( singer_id ), 
    FOREIGN KEY (song_name) REFERENCES songs(song_name) 
) ENGINE=INNODB;
